[2]
Date: Wed 8 Dec 2004
From: David Dassey <ddassey@ladhs.org>

The moderator's statement about the mouse bioassay [Reversal of the
paralysis by administered botulinum antitoxin confirms the diagnosis. -
Mod.LL] is incorrect [see paragraph 3 in: Botulism, human, botox related -
USA (FL): susp. (03) 20041208.3254].
A better way to say it is: "Prevention of paralysis in mice treated with
type-specific botulinum antitoxin, while untreated mice become paralyzed in
a manner consistent with botulism, provides evidence of botulinum toxin in
the injected specimen. Monovalent [A, B, and E] and trivalent [A-B-E]
antitoxins are available for this purpose, permitting characterization of
the toxin type according to the pattern of survival and paralysis among the
mice.
--
David E Dassey MD
Acute Communicable Disease Control
Department of Health Services
Los Angeles, CA
<ddassey@ladhs.org>
[Drs Elizabeth Bancroft <ebancroft@ladhs.org> (also from the LA County
Department of Health Services) and SB Werner <bwerner@dhs.ca.gov> (from the
California Department of Health Services) also responded to the
misstatement attributed to me. Indeed, they are all correct, the botulinum
toxin's effect on the transmission of acetylcholine is irreversible. The
use of antitoxin in the mouse bioassay confirms the diagnosis by preventing
the paralysis, not reversing it. My moderation had the word "prevention",
not "reversal" in its original version, which was inadvertently changed
after leaving my laptop and arriving at the ProMED-mail site [mea culpa. -
Mod.SH]. ProMED-mail thanks this trio of Californians for their prompt
responses to the error. - Mod.LL]
